First thought, the initial `damos_walk_cancel()` implementation: I see the lock and nulling out of `ctx->walk_control`. The scenario I envision is where `damos_walk_cancel()` grabs the lock, reads `control` (let's say it's *not* NULL, pointing to `C1`), and then gets preempted.  Meanwhile, the thread that called `damos_walk` (Thread A) is blocked in `wait_for_completion(&control->completion)`.  My first inclination is that it's safe because `wait_for_completion` won't return until `complete()` is called.

The question then is, can something else set `ctx->walk_control` to NULL before `damos_walk_cancel()` continues? The code seems clear, `damos_walk_cancel()` and `damos_walk_complete()` are the only functions that clear `ctx->walk_control`, both executed by the `kdamond` thread. So, while `damos_walk_cancel()` is running, no *other* code can clear `ctx->walk_control`, so this case seems safe.

Now, consider the case where `kdamond_fn()` is terminating. There's a new patch that sets `walk_control_obsolete = true` before calling `damos_walk_cancel()`.  Looking at `kdamond_fn()`, if `walk_control_obsolete` is true, any call to `damos_walk()` returns immediately. So that's safe; no new walk control can be registered during the cancel operation.

However, I realize `damos_walk_cancel()` is also called if `list_empty(&ctx->schemes)`. And in *this* case, `walk_control_obsolete` *isn't* set. So, what happens if `damos_walk(ctx, &C1)` is called by Thread A, setting `ctx->walk_control` to `C1`, and then the `kdamond` thread executes `damos_walk_cancel(ctx)`?  `damos_walk_cancel()` locks the mutex, reads `ctx->walk_control` (which is `C1`), and gets preempted. Thread A is blocked in `wait_for_completion(&C1.completion)`. I also realize that the `kdamond_fn()` is a single thread and it cannot loop again while it is preempted inside `damos_walk_cancel()`.

Now, if Thread B calls `damos_walk(ctx, &C2)`, it will hit the `if (ctx->walk_control)` check under the lock and return `-EBUSY`, which seems harmless.

Finally, I zero in on the critical section:  `complete(&control->completion);` where Thread A is woken, returns from `damos_walk()`, and `C1` goes out of scope, but before `ctx->walk_control` is set to NULL.

If Thread B calls `damos_walk(ctx, &C2)` *after* `complete()` but *before* `ctx->walk_control = NULL`, Thread B will see that `ctx->walk_control` is still `C1` and return `-EBUSY`. This is acceptable because Thread B is unable to start a new walk.

If Thread B calls `damos_walk(ctx, &C2)` *after* `ctx->walk_control = NULL`, Thread B succeeds. `ctx->walk_control` then becomes `C2`. The important thing is that `damos_walk_cancel()` is looping and will eventually call itself again if `list_empty(&ctx->schemes)` is true. If that happens, then `C2` will be cancelled as well. That appears safe as well.

The conclusion is that the mutex is crucial, and the `-EBUSY` error return from `damos_walk()` provides the necessary safety net. The code seems robust. I don't see any other concerning race conditions right now.


